VA multi-faceted rendition
p3
sVnews
p4
VShe chose two traditional numbers in Malayalam -Chitti Mandaram Tulasiin Ananda Bhairavi andSabari Malayil Tanga Suryodayamalso in Ananda Bhairavi. If she sang a MeerabhajanPyare Darshan Deejyo,in Sanskrit, she lent her voice toRaghavendra Tava Charanam Bhajamiin Mand, written in Sanskrit by Vyasa Tatvagna Teertha. In Telugu, she chose to render a composition of AnamacharyaYentakalamu Kada, set to music by Rallapalli Ananthakrishna Sarma in Sriragam. In Punjabi, she choseRam Simar, a song written by the 9th guru of Sikhs Theg Bahadur and it received good response.The Gujarati number was the famousVaishnava Janathoof Narasimha Mehta set in Khamas and the one popularised by Subbulakshmi brought back memories of Gandhiji&#8217;s meetings that never went without the rendition of this particular song. Two songs from MarathiPradhama Tula Vandito Kripalain Yaman of Santaram Gavkar and another of Santh TukaramHare Pandurangain Yaman were quite pleasing.Mail medo Vilayadamin Tamil of Sattur Tarpagam inragaVasanthi and then a SanskritMaithri Bhajata Akhilaconcluded the show. S.Venugopal on violin and K.Srinivasa Rao on tabla accompanied her. The tabla was chosen to suit thebhajansin both Carnatic and Hindustani music. Vocalist Thirumala Devi took every care to spell the words in these various languages correctly and her rendition was mellifluous carrying devotional appeal.
